LessonsLearned:
&lt;p&gt;The information gathered and the reconstruction and analysis of the event in question make it possible to identify certain critical points for improvement. These are directly linked to the causes and were also included amongst the instructions issued by the ‘Seveso’ control authorities and health authorities in relation to the accident:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px"&gt;the need for the operations prior to filling drums to include a check that the mobile container to be filled has been equipotentially bonded. When the result of this check is negative, it must not be possible for the filling pumps to be started up;&lt;br&gt;there must be a ban on filling drums when the following conditions arise:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;malfunctioning of the extractor fan serving the drum-filling area or failure to turn it on;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;detection of flammable atmospheres in the drum-filling area, through installation of a system for detecting flammable vapours;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the mobile container has been filled to its maximum capacity for the substance in question;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px"&gt;the risk analysis must cover all possible accident types linked to drum-filling;&lt;br&gt;the risk assessment document for explosions must be updated, ensuring that all items of equipment installed in explosion hazard areas are suitable for those areas based on the area classifications;&lt;br&gt;the safety management system must be re-examined in terms of risk analysis, training of in‑house and outside personnel and operational supervision, particularly for the transfer of flammable liquids into mobile containers. In particular, the training of in-house personnel must be improved as regards the systematic use of the personal protective equipment for product transfer operations.&lt;/p&gt;

Site_Description:
&lt;p&gt;The firm’s business is the wholesale and distribution of chemicals and petrochemicals such as acetates, solvents and thinners as well as the preparation of mixtures of solvents. Its main customers are pharmaceutical companies. Products are primarily delivered by the exclusive transporter XX. Once at the plant, the products are unloaded and stored in underground tanks, into which they are transferred from the tanker trucks by gravity using closed-circuit systems and a flexible hose. The store has 50 underground tanks for commercial use plus three underground gas-oil/diesel tanks for internal use: one tank for gas-oil to power the boiler for the heating system, one tank for diesel used as fuel for the firm’s vehicles and one tank for diesel for the back-up generator. Tanks 15 to 27 differ from the others due to the innovative technological design with which they were built. According to the firm, the objective was to prevent any possibility of product leaking into the ground (double wall with continuous leak monitoring). All the tanks are fitted with a level probe and an atmospheric vent system with flameproof mesh. Lastly, there is a small above-ground tank containing lubricating oils (capacity 4 m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;) located in building C.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Three buildings are used to store various products in drums:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;Building A: Flammable and/or toxic products, products that are toxic for the environment (e.g.&amp;nbsp;butyl acetate, toluene, acetone, ethyl alcohol, methyl alcohol, cyclohexane, etc.);&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building B: Non-flammable and/or non-toxic products (chlorinated compounds, e.g. methylene chloride, perchloroethylene, etc.);&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building C: Flammable products and/or products toxic for the environment (e.g. hexane, heptane, medium oils, white spirit, odourless mineral spirit, lubricating oils, etc.).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Based on the operator’s description, the buildings were built with incombustible, fireproof materials (reinforced concrete frame and brick cladding).&amp;nbsp; The buildings can be easily evacuated in the event of fire, since they have outward-opening metal doors at least 0.70&amp;nbsp;m wide.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The containment basin for leaks comprises perimeter drainage channels located within and around each building, leading to a 100&amp;nbsp;m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; API-separator sedimentation tank.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the case under examination, the buildings are completely isolated from other structures by open spaces. Ventilation is provided by vents in the perimeter walls, at both floor and ceiling level. The buildings have polished concrete floors. Lastly, there is a building whose basement is used as a chemical laboratory used to analyse the incoming and, sometimes, outgoing products to test their purity. This is because pharmaceutical customers require very pure products (to ppm level). That building also features changing rooms and offices on the first floor and guard accommodation on the second floor. The products sold, which again are largely distributed by the exclusive firm XX, leave the plant primarily in bulk form (approx. 95%) in tanker trucks, and to a lesser extent in packaged form (in 200-litre metal drums) on dumper trucks. In the latter case, the products are transferred from the relevant tanks into drums. Flammable products, whether on their own or mixed into requested formulations, are transferred into drums in the designated buildings, i.e. buildings A and C.&lt;/p&gt;

Installation_Description:
&lt;p&gt;The event originated in building A, which has a footprint of around 600&amp;nbsp;m&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; and is where flammable acetates (including the butyl acetate involved in the event) are transferred into drums. As declared by the operator and indicated in the official technical expert’s report, the building is classified as an area with the possible presence of explosive atmospheres (zone 2) within the meaning of Directive 94/9/EC. The building is protected by a manual sprinkler system.&amp;nbsp; Inside the building the drums are stored on roller conveyors where they await loading by forklift onto vehicles for delivery to clients. The roller conveyors are made up of Teflon-coated rollers and are equipotentially bonded to the general earthing system, which is tested twice a year by a notified body. The building features two entirely symmetrical loading stations, known as D1 and D2, each with two pipelines for transferring products and equipped, among other things, with two dispenser nozzles, a scales, an earth clamp and a manually-operated extractor fan. Station D1 has a dispenser nozzle linked to the pipeline fed by the auxiliary pump located outside the building under pavilion D; this is the pipeline on which the accident occurred. The other dispenser nozzle in station D1 is linked to the pipelines fed by underground tanks&amp;nbsp;1-14 located outside the building. Product may be transferred from the underground tanks to Building A either via dedicated pipelines or (in cases where product purity specifications are particularly high, as in the case under examination) via mobile containers (IBCs with a capacity of 1&amp;nbsp;000 litres or ATBs). In such cases, the specific route followed by butyl acetate is as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the product is transferred from underground tank 40 to 1 m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; IBCs in closed circuit at pavilion B using a loading arm;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the filled IBCs are moved manually by forklift from pavilion B to pavilion D, and specifically to the auxiliary pump located outside building A, which is used to transfer the product to drum-filling station D1 via a pipeline;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the product is transferred from the IBC to drum-filling pipeline D1 using the auxiliary pump;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the product is loaded into a drum at station D1 in building A, which is where the event occurred.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When drums are being filled, after the upper rim of the drum has been connected to the earth clamp and the extractor fan has been turned on and placed close to the drum opening, the operative fills it by inserting and turning on the dispenser nozzle and activating the pump. In the case of station D1, where the dispenser nozzle is connected to the auxiliary pump outside, the operative turns on the pump and the extractor fan via a button console located close to the scales. The drum to be filled comes from an overhead roller conveyer (the empty drum conveyor) along which empty drums from the storage area are transferred. The empty drum drops onto a roller conveyer located at ground level, from which it is moved onto a second roller conveyer which transfers it to the scales, which acts as a filling and weighing station. Once it has been filled, the drum is moved to a third roller conveyer shared between the two filling stations and placed onto a line that transfers the full drum to the storage area within the same building. The solvent transfer system works in such a way as to ensure that the velocity of the product within the pipes does not exceed 1 m/s (this is necessary to minimise the formation of electrostatic charges).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Equipment associated with the event: 200-litre ADR-approved metal drum featuring a 2”&amp;nbsp;bung hole and a vent, painted on the outside. After use, the drums received back from clients are refurbished by a specialised firm.&amp;nbsp; The company buys refurbished drums with the desired specifications from that firm. Refurbishment involves, among other things, cleaning and possibly repainting the drum.&lt;/p&gt;

Consequence_Description:
&lt;p&gt;Personal injury/death.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The event caused the death of the worker filling the drum. The fact that the vapours inside the drum ignited caused them to explode. The bottom of the drum was blown off by the pressure that had built up due to the deflagration inside, and the liquid in the drum, which was by now in flames, spilled out violently, partly onto the ground and partly onto the worker, who was burned on his face, torso, upper and lower limbs &amp;ndash; a total of 80% of his body &amp;ndash; sparing only his upper thorax, inner abdomen, hands and the soles of his feet (because of the protective gloves and shoes). The worker was immediately given first aid and taken to hospital, where he died of complications 15 days later (on 31 July 2015).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Material damage.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The fire spread to only a minor extent because it was fuelled essentially only by the spilled liquid. It caused limited damage to drum-filling station D1 inside building A. During the inspection committee&amp;rsquo;s site inspection, station D1 still showed evident damage caused by direct flame exposure, both at ground level and on devices and equipment up to a height of around 6&amp;nbsp;m above ground. As indicated in the official technical expert&amp;rsquo;s document and declared by the operator:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;all the components present were damaged: the roller conveyor delivering drums, the roller conveyor bringing drums to the scales, the button console, the scales, the local extractor fan and the dispenser nozzle. After the event, the dispenser nozzle used to fill the drum displayed signs of a blast;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;the drum-filling pipeline near D1 and the roller conveyor delivering drums were also damaged to a lesser but still significant extent. In the surrounding area, five drums exploded and their bottoms and lids can be seen in the photos taken by the official technical expert. One of the exploded drums lost its bottom, whilst the lid, without the cap, remained attached. There were caps on the lids of all the other exploded drums. The vapour extractor was found burned and positioned above the drum. There was no evidence to state whether it had been turned on. The auxiliary pump was found switched on.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Overall, the damage observed can be attributed to the results of a pool fire resulting from the spillage onto the ground of a relatively minor quantity of flammable liquid and a number of deflagrations within some drums.&lt;/p&gt;
